AdditionalComment: I couldn't find any 100% correct answer to the question shown at 33% of survey completion.
Web Service design and use is only a small part of my duties.

DeveloperPerspective[other]: Offered perspectives are unclear. For me a REST API is offered for consumption to both end users (browsers) and automated systems.

AdditionalComment: In general, none of the questions were related to REST or RESTful HTTP. Instead it was a comprehension test for Swagger. Most questions aimed at extracting request semantics from the URI structure, although REST considers URIs to be opaque identifiers. This is IMHO pretty misleading when this survey aims at REST and RESTfulness. Also the question with the empty bearer token was odd to me. Since the screenshot did not require any auth, none of the answers looked correct to me. I would have expected a 401 if the bearer token is empty or wrong.

You "REST" ApI example where presented in a swagger like style. I'd rather classify it as "HTTP API". Often the Status Codes where missleading or unprecise but the meaning could - in this "test" - be deducted from the request and documentation.  Because of this I am not sure if my answers lead to the correct impression.

DeveloperPerspective[other]: There is no reason this wouldn't be better understandable and usable if it were GraphQL
AdditionalComment: Rest has way too many possibilities where the functionality of the API is dependant of the interpretation of (non existing) doc. GraphQL basically forces to be structured and documented as well as introduce type safety. So just use GraphQL

Well, all of the API examples didn't have any description so one had to guess based on the URL path. I've been taught that it is dangerous to read to deep into an URL, yet it was the only source of information. So basically that's the reason I rated all APIs bad to understand. Those with more parameters had more context, so it was easier to understand. I would have preferred this context to be given by description instead of parameters. So if you interpret my ratings you could come to the conclusion that I think: Parameters - the more the merrier! That's actually not the case. However context (almost always) helps. Also the one question with the "delete queue" and the GET request: I have no clue what it does. I just hope that it doesn't actually delete the queue instead. As it shouldn't, it's a GET, isn't it? Well, it's not that I've not seen APIs delete stuff on a GET request. I host HOPE it's not what it does. Would I rely on it: Probably not… Good luck for the further studies and don't read too much into API endpoints! ;-)

Not adhering to the common use of HTTP Verbs is very confusing, same as not using path parameters for selecting specific items. (e.g. POST for a search with body instead of query, GET for retrieving items with query instead of path)

Sometimes I was not sure about the answers or none of the given options fitted. Would have been good to have another option for such cases (e.g. "other" or "not sure" or "none of them") or to tell attendees to choose the best guess.
